 well as publicists and women's organizations—who all identified industrial design as a vital means of economic recovery, social reform, and even moral regeneration. These cultural battles took on heightened importance precisely because the stakes were nothing less than the very shape and significance of West German domestic modernity. Betts tells the rich and far-reaching story of how and why commodity aesthetics became a focal point for fashioning a certain West German cultural identity. This book is situated at the very crossroads of German industry and aesthetics, Cold War politics and international modernism, institutional life and visual culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aIndustrial designzGermanyxHistory. 7aARCHITECTURE / History / General.2bisacsh  a20th century german culture.  a20th century industrial design.  aarchitects.  aautomobiles.  abauhaus.  abraun.  acold war politics.  acommodity aesthetics.  aconsumer appliances.  aconsumer groups.  acultural identity.  acultural studies.  adesign.  adesigners.  adomestic modernity.  aeconomic recovery.  afurniture.  agermany.  ahistorical.  aindustrial culture.  aindustry.  ainstitutional life.  ainternational modernism.  amaterialism.  amodernism.  amodernity.  amoral regeneration.  anation state.  apolitics.  apostwar germany.  asocial reform.  avisual culture.  awerkbund.  awest germany.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025384140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094135940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520941359423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520941359/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000